title: For Sale:  Allin Trapdoor Conversion Springfield Model 1866       Made Famous in the Indian Wars
postcontent:
Allin Trapdoor Conversion Springfield Model 1866
Made Famous in the Indian Wars
After the American Civil War, the United States military was slow to adopt new technological advances in firearms and opted to retrofit their enormous surplus inventory of Model 1861 type muskets to fire cartridges. Many different types of conversions were conceived and implemented.
 
These conversions were the main infantry weapon of the West and played a large role in the Indian Wars of the late 19th century. 25,000 Model 1863s received the Allin Conversion, enabling them to be loaded via the breach through a “trapdoor” mechanism.
 
This one is in .50 centerfire.
 
Lock is dated “1864” rear the hammer. The federal eagle is forward of the hammer as is “U.S. Springfield”. “1866” over an eagle head is visible on the trapdoor mechanism.
Serial Number: none
 
Caliber: .50 centerfire
 
Bore is in nice condition and all parts mechanically functional.
 
Overall condition as seen in photos.

postcontent: Here's an exceptionally nice, all original, M1 Garand .30-06 rifle! Manufactured by Harrington & Richardson (H&R Arms) in late 1954/early 1955, this rifle would be difficult to upgrade. HRA produced M1 rifles between 1953-1956 and they are noted as being among the best quality Garands ever made. This rifle was purchased through the Civilian Marksmanship Program (CMP) as an all original "Collector Grade" rifle. The continuity of finish & minimal wear on the various parts indicates that this rifle indeed remains "as issued" and is not just a bunch of HRA parts put back together. The original parkerized finish rates about 96-97% overall. There are a few minor handling marks, but there is no rust or any pitting. The chamber end of the barrel is still "in the white" indicative of original finish.

title: For Sale:  Custom Pre- Rem Marlin 444 XLR
postcontent:
Up for sale I have my Marlin 444 XLR Stainless. This a pre-Remington (JM stamped, but not removing the rail)  I've owned for about 10 years. This was originally purchased to replace my old 444S that I lost in a home burning down sometime ago.Shortened the barrel to 18.5in (not ported as these don't really buck that much and too much flash), and replaced stock lever w/ a factory stainless hoop. XS sights and rail, Leatherwood long eye relief scope, and nice butt stock shell holder. Wife nicknamed it "The Moose Masher" as I have taken quite a bit of game with it, including the moose I did indeed mash with one 300 grain Belt Mountain Punch slug (of which I have 2 full boxes remaining available for sale).
Minor nicks, scratches, etc. and actually looks better than I would expect considering I don’t baby many things. 
The crowned barrel reduction and lever swap (not for a John Wayne look, but to facilitate gloved hands when it’s below 0 here in Wisconsin) were performed by a reputable local gunsmith and not one of my experimental hacks. Includes the Hi-Lux 2x7 scope with Warne QD rings, the Lyman tang sight (used this sight exclusively until the Express sights and rail were installed and been kept on hand for backup), etc. per the pics.
If you've ever owned one, you know this round kicks ass. I also have a great deal of ammo ranging from Hornady to heavy Grizzly and Buffalo Bore available as well. Let me know if you're interested and can forward additional info, pics, etc. I will ship ammo UPS ground, free if you want to buy enough.FFL to FFL only on the rifle and I will cover the outbound FFL shipping.
